		<div class = "central_body">
			<h1> Windows SideBar <i style="color: var(--c_ok)" class="fa fa-windows"></i> </h1>
			<h2> Content and Features </h2>
			
			<div class="box" style="display: inline-block; max-width: calc(100% - (126px + 64px))">
				<p>
				As the name suggests, this software is strictly Windows only, Linux version is not planned.
				</p>
				<p>
				Windows SideBar is an highly customizable desktop tool, which adds a bar on the right side of the screen.
				The bar has an analog clock, which Windows 10 lacks of by default, and a customizable amount of buttons.
				</p>
				<p>
				The buttons can either run a program, open a website, or even run a console command.
				</p>
				<p>
				Colors can be customized.
				</p>
				<p>
				By default an additional decoration is active which renders some nice particle effects behind your taskbar;
				if you don't see the particles, you have to enable taskbar transparency.
				</p>				
			</div>
			<img src="/sidebarshow.png" alt="HTML5 Icon" align="right" width=126px/>
			
			<div style="width: 100%; overflow: hidden">
				<img src="/bottombarshow.png" alt="HTML5 Icon" align="right"/>
			</div>
			<h2> Current State </h2>
			<div class="box">
				The program itself has been completed. Right now it only lacks the following extra features:
				<ul>
					<li>Customization and settings window</li>
					<li>Drag&ampDrop links and programs to automatically add a button</li>
					<li>Support for different taskbar positions</li>
					
				</ul>
			</div>
